<!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--note do not remove this category during translation--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)--><!--Jinshi (Japan)-->

'''Shinshi''' (進士) refers to the third civil service examination conducted by the {{ill|Ministry of Ceremonial|ja|式部省|1=Shikibu-shō|lt=Ministry of Ceremonial Affairs|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ministry of Ceremonial|13=User:Immanuelle/Shikibu-shō|qq=}} under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ritsuryō system|qq=}}, following {{ill|Shūsai|ja|秀才 (日本)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shūsai|qq=}} and {{ill|Meikyō|ja|明経|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meikyō|qq=}}. It is also called the '''Shinshi Examination''' (進士試, Shinshishi).

== Overview ==

To recruit individuals widely knowledgeable and scholarly, candidates were tested on two essays addressing "critical affairs of state" (治国之要務) called {{ill|Jimusaku|ja|時務策|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jimusaku|qq=}}, as well as ten passages: seven from the {{ill|Wenxuan|ja|文選_(書物)|lt=Selections of Refined Literature|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wenxuan|qq=}} and three from the {{ill|Erya|ja|爾雅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Erya|qq=}}. This test involved {{ill|Chōshi|ja|帖試|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōshi|qq=}}, which required memorization and oral recitation of selected blank portions. 

Performance was evaluated in three grades: "excellent" (甲), "good" (乙), and "passable" (丙). Candidates graded 甲 or 乙 were considered successful. Those achieving 甲 were a11ointed to the Rank of {{ill|Jugoi-no-Ge|ja|従八位下|1=Junior Eighth Rank|lt=Junior Eighth Rank, Lower Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jugoi-no-Ge|13=User:Immanuelle/Junior Eighth Rank|qq=}}, while those achieving 乙 were granted {{ill|Daisoi-no-Jō|ja|大初位上|1=Greater Initial Rank|lt=Greater Initial Rank, Upper Grade|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daisoi-no-Jō|13=User:Immanuelle/Greater Initial Rank|qq=}}. However, passing required flawless essays in terms of both content and reasoning, and a high standard for Chōshi responses (perfect for 甲, six or more correct for 乙). As a result, the exam was notoriously difficult. Notable examples of 甲 achievers include {{ill|Kibi no Makibi|ja|吉備真備|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kibi no Makibi|qq=}}, who was selected as a student for the {{ill|Kentōshi|ja|遣唐使|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kentōshi|qq=}} mission in {{ill|716 (Reiki 2)|ja|霊亀2nd year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/716 (Reiki 2)|qq=}}.

While the Ranks awarded to successful candidates were lower than those of {{ill|Shūsai|ja|秀才|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shūsai|qq=}} and other examinations, the high difficulty resulted in low participation. Consequently, the Shinshi system was abolished during the {{ill|Jōgan era|ja|貞観 (日本)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōgan era|qq=}} in the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}. Thereafter, the term "Shinshi" referred to {{ill|Bunshōsei|ja|文章生|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunshōsei|qq=}} (students of historiography) selected through tests in classical Chinese composition.

== References ==
* {{ill|Tadao Nomura|ja|野村忠夫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tadao Nomura|qq=}}, "Shinshi," in {{ill|Kokushi Daijiten|ja|国史大辞典 (昭和時代)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kokushi Daijiten|qq=}} 7 (Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1986) ISBN 978-4-642-00507-4.  
* Tadao Nomura, "Shinshi," in {{ill|Nihonshi Daijiten|ja|日本史大事典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihonshi Daijiten|qq=}} 3 (Heibonsha, 1993) ISBN 978-4-582-13103-1.  
* {{ill|Shinpei Kotō|ja|古藤真平|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinpei Kotō|qq=}}, "Shinshi," in {{ill|Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|ja|日本歴史大事典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|qq=}} 2 (Shōgakukan, 2000) ISBN 978-4-09-523002-3.  

